Title: Primary keys using UUID v7 are (potentially) an HR violation
Description: I'm building an applicant tracking system where I use UUID v7 for primary keys on the users table. Then I discovered an unintended consequence: UUID v7 embeds a timestamp, which creates a privacy leak. If a user's account was created in 2025 with an ID of 0199b901-fb2b-7745-9e62-019fe1c0ddca, anyone can extract that timestamp and infer a minimum age for the user. The older the account, the older we know the applicant must be, enabling unintentional age discrimination through what should be an opaque identifier.
